1. # Component Disposal
2. 
3. Always use `IAsyncDisposable` (not `IDisposable`). Returns `ValueTask` — works for sync and async cleanup.
4. 
5. ## When to Implement
6. 
7. Implement when component owns: event subscriptions, timers, `CancellationTokenSource`, or JS interop references (`IJSObjectReference`, `DotNetObjectReference<T>`). Otherwise skip disposal.
8. 
9. ## Pattern — Sync Cleanup
10. 
11. ```razor
12. @implements IAsyncDisposable
13. @inject NavigationManager Navigation
14. 
15. @code {
16.     protected override void OnInitialized()
17.         => Navigation.LocationChanged += HandleLocationChanged;
18. 
19.     private void HandleLocationChanged(object? sender, LocationChangedEventArgs e) { }
20. 
21.     public ValueTask DisposeAsync()
22.     {
23.         Navigation.LocationChanged -= HandleLocationChanged;
24.         return ValueTask.CompletedTask;
25.     }
26. }
27. ```
28. 
29. ## Pattern — JS Interop Cleanup
30. 
31. ```razor
32. @implements IAsyncDisposable
33. @inject IJSRuntime JS
34. 
35. @code {
36.     private IJSObjectReference? module;
37. 
38.     protected override async Task OnAfterRenderAsync(bool firstRender)
39.     {
40.         if (firstRender)
41.             module = await JS.InvokeAsync<IJSObjectReference>("import", "./js/myModule.js");
42.     }
43. 
44.     public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
45.     {
46.         if (module is not null)
47.         {
48.             try { await module.DisposeAsync(); }
49.             catch (JSDisconnectedException) { } // Circuit already gone
50.         }
51.     }
52. }
53. ```
54. 
55. ## Anti-pattern — Timer (Don't)
56. 
57. Prefer `Task.Delay` polling loops (see SKILL.md). If you must use a timer, use `async void` to avoid discarding the `InvokeAsync` task:
58. 
59. ```razor
60. @using System.Timers
61. @implements IAsyncDisposable
62. 
63. @code {
64.     private Timer? timer;
65. 
66.     protected override void OnInitialized()
67.     {
68.         timer = new Timer(1000);
69.         timer.Elapsed += OnTimerElapsed;
70.         timer.Start();
71.     }
72. 
73.     private async void OnTimerElapsed(object? sender, ElapsedEventArgs e)
74.     {
75.         try
76.         {
77.             await InvokeAsync(() => { count++; StateHasChanged(); });
78.         }
79.         catch (Exception ex)
80.         {
81.             await DispatchExceptionAsync(ex);
82.         }
83.     }
84. 
85.     public ValueTask DisposeAsync()
86.     {
87.         timer?.Dispose();
88.         return ValueTask.CompletedTask;
89.     }
90. }
91. ```
92. 
93. `Timer.Elapsed` fires on thread-pool thread. `async void` is the only correct handler signature — it awaits `InvokeAsync` and routes errors via `DispatchExceptionAsync`.
94. 
95. ## Rules
96. 
97. - **Don't** call `StateHasChanged` in `DisposeAsync` — renderer is tearing down.
98. - **Do** null-check fields created in lifecycle methods — `DisposeAsync` may run before `OnInitializedAsync` completes.
99. - **Do** catch `JSDisconnectedException` when disposing JS refs — circuit may be gone.
100. - **Do** unsubscribe all event handlers (`-=`) — subscriptions on long-lived objects leak the component.
101.

